  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Background: In an international randomised controlled trial we studied how patient
      self-reported symptoms improved after either a stapled anopexy operation or a diathermy
      excision of the haemorrhoids.

      Methods: The study involved 18 hospitals in Sweden, Denmark and the UK. Two hundred and seven
      patients were randomised. After exclusion of 27 patients, 90 in both groups were operated and
      followed one year. Patients provided self-reported symptoms before surgery and after 1 year.
      A patient diary obtained daily self-reported postoperative pain scores (VAS). Surgeons
      evaluated the anal anatomy before surgery and after 1 year.
    </textblock>
